{"cursor":"24314","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Oil dispersants' are a mixture of surfactants and solvents that break up an oil\nspill into droplets. By breaking it up, microbes and the environment can more\neasily biodegrade the oil. A mixture of oil and water is normally unstable, but\ncan be stabilized with the addition of surfactants. Surfactants improve\ninteraction at the oil-water junction, decreasing surface energy. Dispersants\nhave had negative environmental effects due to their toxicity; however,\nreformulated dispersants have been accepted by the United States Environmental\nProtection Agency (EPA).\n","linknr":328,"url":"Oil_dispersants","recorded":1362512427,"links":27,"instances":["chemistry","physics"],"pdf":["http://www.iosc.org/papers_posters/00015.pdf","http://www.oilspillcommission.gov/sites/default/files/documents/Updated%20Dispersants%20Working%20Paper.pdf"],"categories":["Environmental chemistry","Environmental issues","Oil spill remediation technologies"],"headings":["History","Theory","Thermodynamics","{{anchor|Types of Surfactants}}Surfactant types","{{anchor|HLB Values}}HLB values","{{anchor|Comparative Industrial Formulations}}Comparative industrial formulations","{{anchor|Degradation and Toxicity}}Degradation and toxicity","Applications","{{anchor|Methods of Use}}Methods of use","{{anchor|Oil Spills and Dispersants Used}}Oil spills and dispersants used","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Dispersant_Mechanism.jpg/220px-Dispersant_Mechanism.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0c/Oil_with_Surfactant.jpg/220px-Oil_with_Surfactant.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/b/7/ab73ce58fc61f1b365b91a2b012eb844.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/e/9/de99d20e322879dd46f64e44c899dce8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9